WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.480
Alright, this is where it gets real.

2
00:00:02.920 --> 00:00:06.160
Everything up to now has been context and
background.

3
00:00:06.780 --> 00:00:11.360
This module is about what actually comes out
of your mouth when you pick up the phone

4
00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:12.160
and dial.

5
00:00:12.340 --> 00:00:18.140
In this lesson, we're covering step one of
the five-step framework, how to open the

6
00:00:18.140 --> 00:00:18.940
call.

7
00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:24.440
It's short, but it sets the tone for the
entire conversation, so pay attention here.

8
00:00:25.540 --> 00:00:26.340
The intro

9
00:00:26.340 --> 00:00:29.260
is quick, simple, and to the point.

10
00:00:29.620 --> 00:00:33.600
Let me demonstrate. You've got about 15
seconds to set

11
00:00:33.600 --> 00:00:35.640
the tone for the entire conversation.

12
00:00:36.220 --> 00:00:38.080
15 seconds. That's it.

13
00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:40.820
Here's what a solid opening sounds like.

14
00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:44.780
Hi Jim, this is Andrea with the BMH Group.

15
00:00:45.118 --> 00:00:46.261
How are you doing today?

16
00:00:46.620 --> 00:00:48.100
Great. Sounds like you've

17
00:00:48.100 --> 00:00:52.420
got a pre-qualification for an offer and I'd
like to finalize some details.

18
00:00:52.800 --> 00:00:53.700
When we purchase

19
00:00:53.700 --> 00:00:59.480
properties, we buy them as is, we cover all
closing costs, and there are no commissions

20
00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:00.280
involved.

21
00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:05.360
So by the end of this call, I'll be able to
do one of two things for you.

22
00:01:05.630 --> 00:01:06.630
I can either give you

23
00:01:06.630 --> 00:01:10.190
an approval with an offer or a denial with a
reason.

24
00:01:10.780 --> 00:01:12.280
Did I catch you at a good time?

25
00:01:13.480 --> 00:01:14.340
That's it.

26
00:01:14.640 --> 00:01:20.020
That's the whole thing, but every piece of
that is doing something specific.

27
00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:22.660
So let me break it down.

28
00:01:23.460 --> 00:01:27.780
When you say pre-qualified, that frames the
call as

29
00:01:27.780 --> 00:01:30.760
a qualification, not a sales pitch.

30
00:01:31.275 --> 00:01:33.704
The seller doesn't feel like they're being
sold to.

32
00:01:33.807 --> 00:01:35.677
They feel like they're being evaluated.

33
00:01:36.060 --> 00:01:37.940
It completely flips the dynamic.

34
00:01:38.439 --> 00:01:39.820
Suddenly they're wondering if

35
00:01:39.820 --> 00:01:43.200
they qualify instead of wondering how to get
you off the phone.

36
00:01:44.320 --> 00:01:46.620
When you say approval with an offer

37
00:01:46.620 --> 00:01:50.800
or denial with a reason, that creates
intrigue.

38
00:01:51.660 --> 00:01:55.460
Now they're thinking, wait, am I going to
qualify

39
00:01:55.460 --> 00:01:59.680
instead of, oh great, another person trying
to buy my house?

40
00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:02.100
It shifts their whole mental frame.

41
00:02:03.380 --> 00:02:06.440
And when you ask, did I catch you at a good
time?

42
00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:08.520
You're handling the first objection,

43
00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:11.300
which is always time right up front.

44
00:02:11.680 --> 00:02:15.580
If they say no, you schedule a callback, no
big deal.

45
00:02:15.580 --> 00:02:19.340
If they say yes, you've just gotten
permission to continue.

46
00:02:19.820 --> 00:02:23.740
That's huge. Now, right after the intro,

47
00:02:24.160 --> 00:02:25.940
I want you to say this.

48
00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:31.440
Perfect. What I want you to do is grab a pen
and paper because there's

49
00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:35.880
going to be some information you'll want to
jot down as we go through this.

50
00:02:36.140 --> 00:02:37.140
Then give them your

51
00:02:37.140 --> 00:02:43.580
name, spell your last name out for them, give them
the company name, and at the end of the call,

53
00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:47.340
give them your phone number and ask them to
repeat it back to you.

54
00:02:48.620 --> 00:02:50.140
Why does this matter so much?

55
00:02:50.680 --> 00:02:53.880
Think about it. You're taking control of the
conversation.

57
00:02:54.133 --> 00:03:00.734
Whatever this person was doing before you called,
watching TV, making lunch, scrolling through

59
00:03:00.734 --> 00:03:04.720
their phone, you've now redirected their entire
attention to you.

60
00:03:05.040 --> 00:03:07.520
They're getting up, finding a pen, sitting

61
00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:09.640
down, writing things down.

62
00:03:10.120 --> 00:03:16.040
That's engagement. It's also a compliance
test, and I mean that in

63
00:03:16.040 --> 00:03:22.220
the best way. If they'll do what you ask,
grab a pen, write things down, repeat your

64
00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:23.020
number back,

65
00:03:23.100 --> 00:03:25.040
you know they're actually engaged.

66
00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:29.180
They're present. If they can't repeat your
phone number back to you,

67
00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:33.640
they weren't really writing it down and you
don't have real engagement yet.

68
00:03:34.460 --> 00:03:35.260
Good to know.

69
00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:38.640
And you're also building trust early.

70
00:03:39.160 --> 00:03:42.080
You're giving them your real information,
your real name,

71
00:03:42.440 --> 00:03:47.280
your real number. You're saying, here's who
I am, here's how to reach me.

72
00:03:47.366 --> 00:03:48.557
That's different from the

73
00:03:48.557 --> 00:03:51.777
other callers who just wanted a quick number
and then hung up.

74
00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:55.320
You're a real person and you're

75
00:03:55.320 --> 00:04:01.440
proving it. One quick thing to ask early on,
are you speaking on a landline or a cell

76
00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:02.640
phone? Simple

77
00:04:02.640 --> 00:04:06.420
question, but it determines your entire
follow-up strategy.

78
00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:09.100
Cell phone means you can text them.

79
00:04:09.470 --> 00:04:11.709
Landline means you've got to call them at
home.

80
00:04:12.460 --> 00:04:15.100
That one little detail changes how you stay
in

81
00:04:15.100 --> 00:04:20.140
touch going forward. One last mindset before
you go deeper.

82
00:04:20.679 --> 00:04:22.346
When you move into the conversation

83
00:04:22.346 --> 00:04:26.466
itself, assume they're motivated until
proven otherwise.

84
00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:28.860
Don't start the call trying to figure

85
00:04:28.860 --> 00:04:31.060
out if this person is worth your time.

86
00:04:31.400 --> 00:04:35.740
Flip it. Assume this is a deal and your job
is to find out

87
00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:39.220
what's driving them. And here's the ratio
that matters.

88
00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.100
You should be listening 80% of the time,

89
00:04:43.260 --> 00:04:48.620
talking 20. It's a conversation, not an
interrogation.

90
00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:51.200
That's your opening.

91
00:04:51.800 --> 00:04:58.060
15 seconds to flip the dynamic, take control,
and build trust before you ever talk about

92
00:04:58.060 --> 00:04:58.860
the house.

93
00:04:58.860 --> 00:05:04.860
Next up is step two, the fact find, where
that 80% of listening actually

94
00:05:04.860 --> 00:05:06.500
happens. I'll see you there.
